SaaS Roadmap Checklist
Use this checklist to ensure roadmap coverage is complete. Do not dump every item into the answer; select what matters for the user's product, phase, and audience.
Strategy Inputs
Product category, core workflow, target personas, buyer, and user.
Business model: free trial, freemium, seat-based, usage-based, tiered, enterprise contract, marketplace, or services-assisted.
Launch path: prototype, MVP, pilot, private beta, public launch, product-led growth, sales-led enterprise, or agency handoff.
Deployment model: multi-tenant SaaS, single-tenant, region-specific, private cloud, hybrid, or on-prem.
Constraints: budget, timeline, team skills, existing stack, regulatory exposure, data sensitivity, expected traffic, uptime target, and vendor preferences.
Success metrics: activation, retention, conversion, revenue, usage, latency, reliability, support volume, gross margin, and sales cycle velocity.
Phase Template
For each phase, define:
Objective and target users.
User-facing features and admin or operations features.
Architecture and infrastructure changes.
Data model, migrations, storage, retention, and backups.
APIs, events, webhooks, background jobs, and integration boundaries.
Authentication, authorization, tenancy, auditability, and access control.
Billing, entitlements, invoices, taxes, trials, dunning, and subscription lifecycle.
Security, privacy, compliance, and legal readiness.
Testing strategy and release quality bar.
DevOps, environments, CI/CD, rollback, and release process.
Observability, analytics, support tooling, and runbooks.
Technical debt accepted, debt retired, and debt watchlist.
Team needs, ownership, delivery milestones, and dependencies.
Exit criteria and go/no-go gates.
Common Phases
MVP
Ship the smallest paid, pilot-ready, or learning-ready workflow.
Include account setup, core tenant model, basic roles, primary workflow, minimal admin, billing-ready data model, error tracking, backups, and manual support paths.
Prefer a modular monolith, managed services, and explicit domain boundaries over premature microservices.
Gate: target users can complete the primary workflow, data is recoverable, billing path is credible, and incidents can be triaged.
Early Traction
Harden onboarding, permissions, data import and export, customer feedback loops, analytics, audit events, support tools, and integration edges.
Add migration discipline, staging parity, seed or test data, basic load testing, and rollback paths.
Gate: pilot customers can run real workloads with acceptable support burden.
Public Launch
Add production SLOs, incident process, customer communications, production monitoring, security review, abuse controls, billing automation, tax or invoice handling, and support workflows.
Improve performance for expected launch traffic and document capacity assumptions.
Gate: launch load is modeled, payment lifecycle works, support can respond, and rollback is rehearsed.
Growth
Introduce caching, queues, read replicas, search, analytics warehouse, service extraction, event-driven workflows, regional strategy, or dedicated workers only when triggers justify them.
Mature CI/CD, infrastructure as code, secrets management, cost tracking, data lifecycle, operational runbooks, and ownership boundaries.
Gate: bottlenecks are measured, reliability and cost remain within targets, and engineering can ship without repeated operational disruption.
Enterprise Readiness
Add SSO/SAML/OIDC, SCIM, granular RBAC or ABAC, audit logs, data residency, configurable retention, legal holds, customer-managed keys if required, security questionnaires, SOC 2 or relevant compliance path, advanced reporting, sandbox tenants, and enterprise support model.
Provide integration governance, versioned APIs, webhook reliability, admin analytics, procurement support, and account management workflows.
Gate: enterprise sales, security review, onboarding, support, and compliance obligations are repeatable.
Architecture Decisions To Call Out
Modular monolith versus services.
Multi-tenant isolation model.
Data model ownership and migration policy.
API style, versioning, SDKs, and webhook reliability.
Sync versus async processing.
Build versus buy for auth, billing, analytics, notifications, search, support, CRM, and data pipelines.
Region, residency, and disaster recovery strategy.
Operational ownership, incident response, and support model.
Scalability Triggers
Users: concurrent users, monthly active users, tenants, admins, seats, and enterprise accounts.
Traffic: requests per minute, job throughput, webhook volume, API consumers, and background queue depth.
Data: database size, table growth, query latency, file or object storage, analytics volume, and retention requirements.
Reliability: uptime target, recovery time objective, recovery point objective, incident frequency, and customer escalation severity.
Compliance: regulated data, enterprise security review, audit requirements, data residency, privacy commitments, and contractual obligations.
Organization: number of engineers, release frequency, support tickets, sales commitments, implementation workload, and handoff needs.
Cost: cloud spend per customer, gross margin pressure, vendor overage, and operational labor per account.
Release Gates
Product: critical user journeys pass, onboarding works, product analytics are instrumented, and core jobs are completed by target users.
Quality: automated tests cover core flows, migrations are tested, critical browser or device targets are verified, and acceptance criteria are explicit.
Security: dependency scan, secrets review, authorization checks, access logs, data privacy review, and abuse controls are complete.
Performance: expected load is tested, slow queries are identified, capacity plan is documented, and rollback has been rehearsed.
Operations: dashboards, alerts, backups, restore test, runbooks, customer support path, and incident owner are ready.
Business: pricing and packaging are configured, billing is tested, terms and privacy materials are ready, and sales or support teams can explain the release.
Output Guidance
Prefer phase tables for executive readability and short bullets for risks, gates, and triggers.
Include concrete deliverables and measurable exit criteria.
Separate immediate priorities from later-stage investments.
Distinguish must-have now, design for later, and defer safely.
Surface critical path dependencies early.
Keep the roadmap opinionated but adaptable to the user's constraints.
